sentences: Kevin Moore (born May 26, 1967) is an American keyboardist, vocalist, composer, and founder of the Chroma Key music project.
Starting with 1998's Dead Air for Radios, he has released electronica, ambient music through his solo project Chroma Key.
This led Moore to form OSI with Fates Warning guitarist Jim Matheos in 2002, a band which combines progressive metal with electronica.
The fourth OSI album, Fire Make Thunder, was released in March 2012.
The soundtrack for the first film, Okul, was released in 2004 as Ghost Book.
The soundtrack for the second film, Küçük Kiyamet, entitled Shine, was released in 2010.

After graduating from high school in 1985, Moore briefly attended SUNY Fredonia, where he studied classical music, before returning home to form the band Majesty with childhood friends guitarist John Petrucci and bassist John Myung, who had recruited drummer Mike Portnoy (a fellow Long Islander) during their short enrollment at Berklee College of Music.
Dream Theater's debut studio album was 1989's When Dream and Day Unite, which earned the group comparisons to well-known progressive rock bands such as Rush and Queensrÿche.
Their big breakthrough, however, came in 1992 with the album Images and Words, featuring the band's highest charting single to date, "Pull Me Under".
In 1994, the band released its third studio album, Awake, which was the band's highest charting album to date with Moore, reaching #32.
Most of these songs were later released in 1999 on a limited-edition CD called This is a Recording.
In 1998, Moore released his first solo album, Dead Air For Radios, under the name Chroma Key on his self-created record label, Fight Evil Records.
In 2000, Moore moved to Los Angeles, California, where he recorded the digitally-themed You Go Now.
In 2004, Moore scoured public domain films looking for one that exuded a certain mood, intending to write a pseudo-soundtrack to it.
The film he chose was Age 13, an educational film from the 1950s, originally for use in schools.
In 2003, Fates Warning guitarist Jim Matheos invited Moore to work with him on a new musical project.
Moore had worked with Matheos before, appearing as guest keyboardist on Fates Warning's 1989 album Perfect Symmetry, 1997 album A Pleasant Shade of Gray and 2000 album Disconnected.

In April 2006, Moore and Matheos released a second OSI album called Free, a collaboration made easier by Moore's temporary relocation to Montreal, Quebec, Canada.
In the spring of 2006, Moore and Matheos alluded to possible tourdates in the support of the album, but nothing ever materialized.
In September 2008, Moore announced on his website that he had been working for several months with Jim Matheos and drummer Gavin Harrison (of the band Porcupine Tree) on the third OSI album.
Blood was released in April 2009.
OSI's fourth album, Fire Make Thunder, was released in March 2012.
In 2004, Moore relocated to Istanbul, Turkey, and composed the soundtrack to the horror film Okul (The School) which was subsequently released as a solo record titled Ghost Book.
In 2006, Moore once again teamed up with Turkish producers for another soundtrack project.
Its soundtrack CD Shine was self-released December 2010 after a funding campaign on Kickstarter Both films, Okul and Küçük Kıyamet, were based on books written by Turkish author Doğu Yücel.
In March 2007, Moore played an hour-long concert, which was held at Turkey's Balo Stage on March 23.
In April 2007, Moore announced plans to pre-produce the debut album of Turkish industrial rock band Makine which was released in April 2010.

In September 2013, Fates Warning vocalist Ray Alder revealed in an interview that Moore returned to United States and studied to become a doctor.
According to Alder, Moore was in his third year of medical school as of 2013.
Since 2015, Moore has had a Patreon page for Chroma Key, collecting crowdfunding for song releases.
Since 2020, Moore has been working as a psychiatrist at Trinity Health in Minot, North Dakota.
In a 2019 interview, Dream Theater vocalist James LaBrie stated that he recently got in touch with Moore via texting, and stated that the former band mates are still friends.
This would be the first time Moore had worked with Portnoy since leaving Dream Theater nearly 10 years earlier.
In an April 2007 interview, Sonata Arctica keyboardist Henrik Klingenberg revealed that he was really influenced by Moore when he (Klingenberg) began playing rock music.
Early years ==
Dream Theater's debut studio album was 1989's When Dream and Day Unite, which earned the group comparisons to well-known progressive rock bands such as Rush and Queensrÿche.
On When Dream and Day Unite, he wrote "Status Seeker", "Light Fuse and Get Away", "Only a Matter of Time", and parts of The Killing Hand."
Demos with his lyrics include "Don't Look Past Me, "A Vision" and "Two Far."
In 2000, Moore moved to Los Angeles, California, where he recorded the digitally-themed You Go Now.

The film, Küçük Kıyamet (The Little Apocalypse), tells the horrific tale of a family who decides to rent a summer house by the seaside.

It was described as a try-out to "play some songs for a local crowd...with longer, more elaborate shows planned for the future."
